 by a diverse group of scholars-historians, political scientists, literary scholars, and sociologists-who offer a range of studies of the Marxist heritage focusing on Korea, Japan, India, and China.While some of these essays take up key thinkers in Marxist history or draw attention to outstanding problematics, others focus on national literature and discourse in North and South Korea, the "Mao Zedong Fever" of the 1990s, the implications of Li Dazhao's poetry, and the Indian Naxalite movement. Illustrating the importance of central analytical categories like exploitation, alienation, and violence to studies on the politics of knowledge, contributors confront prevailing global consumerist fantasieswith accounts of political struggle, cultural displacement, and theoretical strategies.Contributors. Tani E. Barlow, Dai Jinhua, Michael Dutton, D. R. Howland, Marshall Johnson, Liu Kang, You-me Park, William Pietz, Claudia Pozzana, Alessandro Russo, Sanjay Seth, Gi-Wook Shin, Sugiyama Mitsunobu, Jing Wang  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCommunism and society. 0aCommunismzAsia. 0aSocialism and society. 0aSocialismzAsia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism.2bisacsh1 aRusso, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarlow, Tani, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPozzana, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowland, D. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJinhua, Dai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDutton, Michael1 aShin, Gi-Wook, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowland, Douglas R.1 aWang, Jing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c